<DOC><DOCNO> AP900710-0167 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-10-90 2245EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-India     07-10 0481</FIRST><SECOND>AM-India,0498</SECOND><HEAD>Sikh Extremists Assassinate Moderate Punjab Leader, Three Aides</HEAD><BYLINE>By HARBAKSH SINGH NANDA</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Militant Sikh separatists shot to deatha moderate Sikh leader, his two bodyguards and their driver onTuesday in the northern state of Punjab, police said.   Balwant Singh, 61, a former finance minister in Punjab and aleading industrialist, was assassinated as he returned home fromhis factory near the state capital of Chandigarh, they reported.   Police blamed Sikh extremists fighting for an independenthomeland in Punjab, a rich farming region bordering Pakistan. Theseparatists say the Hindu-dominated government discriminatedagainst Sikhs.   Sikh gunmen also were blamed for killing six other people acrossthe state on Monday night, United News of India said.   The deaths bring to 1,342 the number of people killed by Sikhextremists in Punjab this year.   In the neighboring state of Jammu-Kashmir, Indian border guardson Tuesday killed six Moslem militants who were trying to crossover into Pakistan in the Kupwara region, about 50 miles northwestof Srinagar, the state capital.   Elsewhere in Kashmir, Moslem separatists killed three Moslemsand a Hindu man in separate incidents, said state governmentofficials, who cannot be identified under briefing rules.   At least 716 people have been killed in Kashmir since Jan. 20,when the government launched a crackdown on separatists fightingfor an independent Kashmiri state.   Indian officials say the Moslem separatists receive weapons andtraining in Pakistan. The Pakistani government denies it.   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto of Pakistan meanwhile met IraqiPresident Saddam Hussein in Baghdad on Tuesday as she continued atour aimed at gaining support in other Moslem countries for herKashmir policy.   Officials accompanying her said she would seek support fortaking up the Kashmir issue at an Islamic foreign ministers'conference in Cairo this month.   Pakistan wants Indian Kashmiris to be allowed to decide theirown future through a U.N.-sponsored plebiscite. India insists thatJammu-Kashmir remain part of India.   In Punjab, Ashok Kapoor, a deputy police superintendent, gavethis account of the assassination:   Three men in a car drew alongside Singh's escort car and openedfire with automatic rifles.   The escort vehicle hit the rear of Singh's car. In the confusionthe attackers fired another burst, killing Singh and the otheroccupants of his car.   Singh, leader of the moderate Akali Dal-Badal Party, was thechief architect of a 1985 accord with the federal government thatsought to fulfill Sikh demands for more autonomy in Punjab.   Sikh extremists opposed the accord, saying it did not meet theirdemand for independence. They targeted Singh and other Sikhmoderates involved in the accord.   Extremist violence led the Indian government to impose directfederal rule on Punjab in May 1987.   Sikhs comprise 2 percent of India's 880 million people but makeup a slight majority in Punjab. Hindus comprise 82 percent of thepopulation nationwide.</TEXT></DOC>